[1] Vaccines
Date: Sat 28 Mar 2015
Source: Bidness Etc [summ., edited]
http://www.bidnessetc.com/38218-glaxosmithkline-plc-adr-and-newlink-genetics-corp-ebola-vaccines-clear-safe/


2 Ebola vaccines clear safety tests in Liberia
----------------------------------------------
The US National Institutes of Health (NIH) said that 2 experimental Ebola vaccines, one from GlaxoSmithKline plc (ADR) and another from NewLink Genetics Corp, "appear to be safe," as per the initial data review of mid-stage clinical trials currently underway in Liberia. The trial subjects were randomly injected with the GSK vaccine, the NewLink vaccine, and a saline shot. The trial volunteers and researchers remained completely unaware of which subject had received which injection. The results were then evaluated on the basis of the subjects' immune system response to the injection in the form of anti-Ebola antibody production.

The positive results, revealed only part-way through the study, give a go-ahead to the next stage of efficiency trials for the 2 vaccines, which would be conducted in additional trial subjects. The researchers intend to enroll around 1500 trial volunteers by April 2015. They are specifically aiming to enroll more women, since they comprised 16 percent of the 1st volunteer group. This would make sure the study results remain free from any gender-based variances. The study is expected to involve continuous monitoring of the volunteers. Blood samples will be collected and tested after 6 and 12 weeks of vaccination.

[Byline: Hannah Ishmael]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
& Roger Feldman <promedrf@gmail.com>

[It is good there is an effort to include women in the vaccine trials. It also is hoped a range of age groups is included. The GSK vaccine uses chimpanzee adenovirus type 3 (ChAd3), as a carrier to deliver genetic material from the Zaire strain of the Ebola virus, which is responsible for the current Ebola outbreak in west Africa. NewLink's vaccine combines an Ebola gene with an attenuated or weakened vesicular stomatitis virus (VSV), a pathogen found in livestock. One of the genes from VSV is replaced by a gene from the Ebola virus. The Ebola gene makes a harmless protein that sits on the virus's outer coat. - Mod.LK]

******
[2] Liberia case fatality
Date: Sat 28 Mar 2015
Source: Al Jazeera [edited]
http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2015/03/liberia-ebola-patient-dies-virus-150328014502981.html


A woman who was Liberia's sole remaining known Ebola patient has died at a treatment centre in the capital, said Francis Ketteh, acting head of the country's Ebola response team. The case was Liberia's 1st in weeks and it set back efforts to halt a virus that has killed more than 10 000 people in Liberia, Guinea, and Sierra Leone.

Authorities say the woman, who died in Monrovia on [Fri 27 Mar 2015], may have contracted Ebola through sex with a survivor, the Reuters news agency reported. "We have been able to trace the people she came in contact with," Ketteh said. "We call on everyone to follow the Ebola preventative measures."

Before the woman fell ill, the Liberian government had hoped to declare the country Ebola-free next month, 42 days after the last patient tested negative for a 2nd time, which would mark double the length of the virus's incubation period.

Health officials have warned the general population that even after areas are declared free of the disease, new cases are possible through sexual transmission. Liberia remains vulnerable to cases imported from Guinea and Sierra Leone.

Starting on Fri [27 Mar 2015], Sierra Leone's 6 million people were being confined to their homes for 3 days as nation resorted again to a sweeping shutdown in a final push to stamp out Ebola. Sierra Leone President Ernest Bai Koroma vowed to do "whatever it takes" to get to 0 cases.

Guinea has reported a rash of new cases of the disease, which had appeared to be on the wane.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This case was the last confirmed case since Liberia was close to being declared Ebola-free, but sadly, 2 additional people are suspected of having Ebola virus disease in the country (one of whom is this patient's 18-year-old daughter), postponing achievement of Liberia's goal to be Ebola-free by April 2015. The World Health Organization (WHO) requires countries prove there are no new cases of Ebola reported for 42 days before that country can be officially declared virus-free (because the incubation period is 21 days). While this is a heartbreaking setback, Liberia is better prepared to manage new cases than at the outset and is still well on the path to reaching the goal of no new cases soon. - Mod.LK]

