[3] Suspected, monitored, quarantined, prevention
28 Mar 2015: Guinea deploys police as Sierra Leoneans cross border while fleeing Ebola lockdown
http://www.startribune.com/world/297879901.html

[According to Guinea spokesperson, Mamadou Alpha Barry, as a response to reports that Sierra Leoneans were crossing the border to flee an Ebola lockdown, Guinea sent security forces to Guinea's southwestern region. The purpose of the lockdown (in which Sierra Leone residents are confined to their homes) is to facilitate contract tracers' ability to locate contacts, and to give educational outreach workers greater opportunity to educate and reinforce the message about Ebola.

28 Mar 2015: Guinea president announces new emergency measures in Ebola fight
http://www.trust.org/item/20150328225809-0d0av/
[President Alpha Conde announced on Sat 28 Mar 2015, new emergency measures enabling authorities to restrict movements in western Guinea (Districts Forecariah, Coyah, Dubreka, Boffa, and Kindia) and a reinforcement of emergency measures for 45 days. Food and medical supplies would be given to the affected communities. In addition to the previously noted 3 doctors in a Conakry hospital who were infected with the virus because of a lack of infection control, 6 additional medical staff across 3 clinics (including doctors) in western Guinea have been infected]

29 Mar 2015: Guinea weighs lockdowns as West Africa continues Ebola fight
http://www.sunherald.com/2015/03/29/6149071_guinea-president-reinforces-emergency.html
[New emergency measures enacted by President Conde include requirement for all burials in the affected areas to be secured by Red Cross or security forces, and all dead bodies will be systematically tested. Mourning ceremonies will be restricted to close family. Lockdowns are part of possible measures that can be implemented.]

27 Mar 2015: Liberia: Ebola fear dwarfs school enrollment in Tewor District
http://allafrica.com/stories/201503271075.html
[The drastic drop in student population is attributed to the Ebola uncertainty among parents to send their children to school.]

29 Mar 2015: Liberia calls for sexual abstinence to cut Ebola transmission risk
http://www.reuters.com/article/2015/03/29/health-ebola-liberia-idUSL6N0WV0PG20150329?rpc=401
[On Sun 29 Mar 2015, Liberia called on Ebola survivors to strictly observe a period of sexual abstinence after recovering from the disease, amid fears the country's last case may have resulted from sexual transmission.]

[Since the pore size of condoms is thought to prevent exposure to the virus, using such prophylactics for a minimum of 3 months may be a more successful approach to preventing Ebola than total abstinence. The latter may be difficult to achieve.

Investigators WD Cardona-Maya and colleagues examined research on male Ebola survivors that was conducted between 1977 and 2007, and found only 4 studies that contained information about Ebola in men's semen. Those 4 studies showed that the Ebola virus persisted in semen for an average of more than 66 days. In one man, the virus lasted for 91 days. See 2014 http://rsx.sagepub.com/content/early/2014/12/15/1933719114563733.full.pdf+html. - Mod.LK]

28 Mar 2015: Norway adjusts its Ebola response
http://www.norwaypost.no/index.php/news/latest-news/30771
[Adjustment in Ebola response is secondary to a greatly reduced infection rate.]

28 Mar 2015 Sierra Leone: Ebola: Police fire tear gas at crowd in Sierra Leone during protests against lockdown
http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-03-29/police-fire-tear-gas-in-sierra-leone-during-ebola-lockdown/6356340
[Police fired tear gas at an angry crowd in Sierra Leone after members of the crowd threw stones at officials during a 3-day national lockdown the government hopes will accelerate the end of the Ebola epidemic. Hundreds of people left their homes in the Devil Hole neighborhood outside the capital to gather at a food collection point. Some residents complained they had not received food. Fighting broke out, until police arrived to scatter the crowd. Elsewhere in the dense slums of eastern and central Freetown, residents defied the lockdown rules and wandered out onto the streets in search of supplies.]

[The lockdown seems like a strong epidemiologic approach, given there is sufficient warning of the lockdown and ample provisions for people to be able to feed their families without leaving home. See following post. - Mod.LK]

28 Mar 2015 Liberia: Sierra Leone Ebola lockdown clashes
http://uk.reuters.com/video/2015/03/29/sierra-leone-ebola-lockdown-clashes?rpc=401&videoId=363666479
[Due to food shortage at distribution point]

28 Mar 2015: 1 year on -- lessons from the Ebola outbreak for WHO
http://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736%2815%2960619-5/fulltext
[The year 2015 will see at least 3 more international, independent investigations into WHO's conduct in the Ebola response. Regrettably, it is likely that the World Health Organization's reputation is going to suffer further in the coming months. The Lancet's focus will be to attempt to draw larger lessons from the Ebola outbreak. In early May 2015, The Lancet will publish a collection of essays on global health security, together with one of the first analyses of the deeper consequences of Ebola]

