26 Mar 2015: 5 people watched for Ebola in Nebraska still healthy
http://www.idahostatesman.com/2015/03/26/3719986_5-people-watched-for-ebola-in.html

27 Mar 2015: Ebola test vaccines appear safe in phase 2 Liberian clinical trial
http://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2015-03/nioa-etv032615.php
[600 trial participants. Candidate vaccine co-developed by National Institute of Allergies and Infectious Diseases scientists and GlaxoSmithKline, and the VSV-ZEBOV candidate vaccine developed by the Public Health Agency of Canada and licensed to NewLink Genetics Corporation and Merck.]

[Information on the breakdown by age and sex of the trial participants would be useful information. - Mod.LK]

Region
------
28 Mar 2015 West Africa: Aid workers racing to defeat Ebola before the rains come
http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2015/03/28/ebola-liberia-guinea-sierra-leone-infection-cdc/70370756/
[Aid workers are rushing to Guinea to try to curtail a worrisome rise in cases of the Ebola virus disease. The mission is urgent because the coming rainy season could hamper travel to remote villages where the disease continues to emerge.]

Research
--------
29 Mar 2015: Ebola remains infectious after the host has died
http://www.digitaljournal.com/science/ebola-remains-infectious-after-the-host-has-died/article/426306#ixzz3VnMHPbG9
[Animal (macaque) studies were performed by the US National Institutes of Health and demonstrated the Ebola virus remains capable of causing infection for at least 7 days post-mortem. The virus also remains capable of potential replication, although not infectious, for up to 70 days post-mortem]

